# Dave Salo Program Audit: ASU 2025-2026 Season
**79 Workouts | Sept 2025 - Dec 2025 | NCAA Championship Season**

---

## Executive Summary

Comprehensive analysis of Dave Salo's Arizona State 2025-2026 training program reveals a **power-based, kick-dominant methodology** built around underwater excellence and race-pace mastery.

**Program DNA:**
- **231 total sets** across 79 workouts
- **226 unique sets** (diversity score: 9.8/10)
- **Kick-focused:** 28.6% kick volume (66 sets)
- **Mixed training:** 30.3% mixed sets (stations, choice, variety)
- **Pull emphasis:** 22.1% pull work (51 sets)

**Philosophy:** Consistently inconsistent - no two weeks identical, preventing staleness while maintaining championship readiness.

---

## 📊 Category Breakdown

| Category | % of Total | Sets | Characteristics |
|----------|-----------|------|-----------------|
| **Mixed** | 30.3% | 70 | Stations, choice stroke, variety work |
| **Kick** | 28.6% | 66 | Dolphin, underwater, breakouts |
| **Pull** | 22.1% | 51 | Paddles, pull-downs, stroke work |
| **IM** | 7.4% | 17 | Multi-stroke combinations |
| **Sprint** | 6.1% | 14 | Max effort, race pace |
| **Stroke** | 3.9% | 9 | Single-stroke focus |
| **Race-Prep** | 1.3% | 3 | Broken swims, pace work |
| **Drill** | 0.4% | 1 | Technique refinement |

### Key Insights

**1. Underwater Dominance**
- 28.6% kick volume (nearly 1 in 3 sets)
- Dolphin kick variations: 2-4-6 patterns, side kicks, vertical kicks
- Breakout drills integrated into most sessions
- Pull-downs as standalone and embedded work

**2. Variety Through Mixed Sets**
- 30.3% of program is "mixed" category
- Station training (power towers, stretch cords, dive work)
- Choice stroke opportunities
- Equipment rotations (fins, paddles, parachutes)

**3. Power > Volume**
- No high-volume threshold grinding
- Emphasis on quality over quantity
- "FAST" descriptor appears throughout
- Load progression with buckets, stretch cords

**4. Race-Pace Integration**
- Broken swims replace traditional straight sets
- 15m/50m splits tracked
- Dive work in diving pool
- Relay takeoff practice

---

## 🏆 Most-Used Set Patterns

### Top Recurring Elements

**1. "Loosen Down" (6x)**
- Appears in almost every workout
- Philosophy: Active recovery, mental reset
- Usually 200 yards choice

**2. Pads/Fins Combinations**
- Equipment rotation within single sets
- Power development with resistance
- Speed work with assistance

**3. Station Work**
- 3-4 stations per practice common
- Combines pool + dryland
- Examples:
  - Station 1: Fast 25 kick + power tower
  - Station 2: Stretch cords full-speed swim
  - Station 3: Dive + fast swim choice stroke

**4. Dolphin Kick Variations**
- 2-4-6 by 25 (building reps)
- Side dolphin kicks (fast)
- Underwater pull-downs + dolphin combos
- Vertical dolphin kicks

---

## 💎 Hidden Gems (Rarely Used Sets)

### Drill Work (1 set total - 0.4%)
**Why so low?**
- Salo integrates "drill elements" into race-pace work
- No isolated drill sessions
- Technique embedded in fast swimming

**Example:**
- `5x100 @ 2:00 dive pace 50 (15m fast, 35 drill) + 50 2nd gear`

### Race-Prep (3 sets - 1.3%)
**Key patterns:**
- Broken 400s: `3x500 + 2-4x75 broken @ 10/50 rest`
- Load progression: `8x25 @ :40 build 1-3, FAST 4 (velocity data collection with bucket loading)`
- Underwater kick: `7x100 @ 1:40 (75 long free tempo, 25 15m underwater kick build)`

### Stroke-Specific (9 sets - 3.9%)
**Why so low?**
- Most freestyle-focused
- Stroke work embedded in IM sets
- Breaststroke pull-downs common but categorized as "pull"

**Examples:**
- `300 fast underwater (Peak Power Breaststroke zone/cali)`
- `8x3 stroke short axis + 4 stroke long axis + 4 breast @ 1:00`
- `1x50 + 1x50 FLY`

---

## 🔍 Program Philosophy Revealed

### 1. **Kick > Pull > Swim**
Traditional hierarchy: Swim → Pull → Kick  
**Salo hierarchy:** Kick → Mixed (stations) → Pull → Swim

**Why?**
- Underwater speed determines race outcomes
- 50% of NCAA races won/lost in first 15m
- Dolphin kick is trainable power

### 2. **Variety Prevents Staleness**
**Diversity score: 9.8/10** (excellent)
- 226 unique sets across 231 total
- Minimal repetition
- Constantly rotating stimuli

**Result:** Athletes stay engaged, avoid adaptation plateau

### 3. **"FAST" is Non-Negotiable**
- Word "FAST" appears in majority of sets
- No "easy aerobic" culture
- Every rep has intent

**Mantra:** "Don't HAVE to do this... I GET to do this"

### 4. **Equipment as Training Tool**
**Not just aids - they're the method:**
- **Fins:** Speed assistance, overload underwater kick
- **Paddles:** Power development, feel for water
- **Parachutes/Buckets:** Resisted sprinting, load progression
- **Stretch Cords:** Full-speed swimming on land
- **Power Towers:** Dryland strength integrated into pool work

### 5. **Station Training**
**3-4 stations per practice:**
- Maximizes pool space utilization
- Keeps groups moving
- Combines pool + dryland + dive work
- Individualizes training within team setting

---

## 📈 Training Evolution Across Season

### September-October (Base Building)
- **Focus:** Power capacity, underwater foundation
- **Volume:** 3,500-4,500 yds/practice
- **Kick emphasis:** Establishing underwater dominance
- **Station work:** Building variety tolerance

### November-December (Championship Prep #1)
- **Focus:** Conference meets, December taper
- **Volume:** Moderate reduction
- **Race-pace:** Broken swims introduced
- **Equipment:** Strategic removal for race simulation

### January (Post-Break Rebuild)
- **Focus:** Technique refinement, power restoration
- **Volume:** Back to 4,000-5,000 yds
- **Kick:** Re-establishing underwater speed
- **Mixed work:** High variety to re-engage

**Note:** Full season extends through March NCAAs (data through December only in this audit)

---

## 🎯 Key Takeaways for Coaches

### What Makes This Work

**1. Underwater is Non-Negotiable**
- 28.6% kick volume minimum
- Every practice includes 500-1,500 yds underwater work
- Pull-downs, breakouts, dolphin variations

**2. Power > Volume**
- Never grinding yardage
- Quality reps with intent
- "FAST" descriptor drives culture

**3. Variety Maintains Engagement**
- Station rotations
- Choice stroke opportunities
- Equipment changes
- No monotony

**4. Race-Pace Embedded Early**
- Broken swims replace traditional straight sets
- 15m splits tracked
- Dive work integrated
- Relay practice regular

**5. Mental Conditioning**
- "I GET to do this" culture
- Active participation vs passive training
- Athlete buy-in through variety

### What to Steal

**For Sprint Programs:**
- Station training structure
- Underwater emphasis (28%+ kick volume)
- Equipment rotation within sets
- "FAST" culture (every rep has intent)

**For Distance Programs:**
- Variety prevents staleness (9.8/10 diversity)
- Mixed work (30%+ of program)
- Active recovery philosophy ("loosen down")
- Technique embedded in race pace (not isolated drills)

**For All Coaches:**
- Consistently inconsistent (no two weeks identical)
- Athlete ownership ("I GET to do this")
- Equipment as method, not aid
- Quality > quantity mindset

